(1188, 3, '2018-01-18 21:31:26', '2018-01-18 21:31:26', 'Hello all!\n\nI am excited to introduce myself as the new Chronic Care Manager replacing our sweet Brittany who has found a job closer to her home. My name is Pamela Schneider. I''m an RN graduate from UL Lafayette. I have been working with Dr. Chen for the past 14 years coordinating his clinical trials with Bendel Medical Research Center. You can find me sitting right up front at his nurse''s station now. I have a lot to learn and I intend to do so with your help. Please, feel free to share all of your frustrations with the program with me. Let me know what works too! Dr. Chen has some exciting plans for this program but we can''t do it without your input and participation!!', 'New CCM Manager', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'new-ccm-manager', '', '', '2018-01-18 21:31:26', '2018-01-18 21:31:26', '', 169, 'http://www.drjchen.com/blog/?topic=new-ccm-manager', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
(1189, 3, '2018-02-08 20:14:37', '2018-02-08 20:14:37', 'Recipe: 	Southwestern Vegetable Soup.\n\n Ingredients: 7 C vegetable broth, 1 C canned dark red kidney beans, with liquid, 1 14.5-ounce can diced tomatoes, with juice, 1 C fresh or frozen cut green beans, 1 C canned, frozen or fresh yellow corn kernels, 1 4-ounce can diced green chilies, ½ C diced onion, Spanish if available, ½ C tomato sauce, 6 corn tortillas, chopped in small pieces, 1½ teaspoons chili powder, dash garlic powder. Garnish: 1 cup grated non-fat soy cheddar and/or soy jack cheese blended, 1 cup crumbled baked corn tortilla chips. Directions: Combine all the soup ingredients and chopped corn tortillas in a large saucepan or soup pot over high heat.   Bring soup to a boil, then reduce the heat and simmer for 45 minutes to 1 hour, or until the soup has thickened and tortilla pieces have mostly dissolved. If salt-free broth is used, add salt to taste near the end of cooking. To serve, ladle about 1½ cups into a bowl. Sprinkle a heaping tablespoon of the grated cheddar/jack cheese blend over the top of the soup, and then a heaping tablespoon of crumbled corn tortilla chips over the cheese. Total calories: 209 Total fat 2 g Sodium 320 mg Carbs 29.9 g Fiber 5.6 g Protein 14.6 g Serving size 1/6 recipe', 'Southwestern Vegetable Soup', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'southwestern-vegetable-soup', '', '', '2018-02-08 20:14:37', '2018-02-08 20:14:37', '', 169, 'http://www.drjchen.com/blog/?topic=southwestern-vegetable-soup', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
(1253, 2, '2019-01-10 19:37:17', '2019-01-10 19:37:17', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Keep a positive attitude.</li>\r\n	<li>Accept that there are events that you cannot control.</li>\r\n	<li>Be assertive instead of aggressive. Assert your feelings, opinions, or beliefs instead of becoming angry, defensive, or passive.</li>\r\n	<li>Learn and practice relaxation techniques; try meditation, yoga, or tai-chi <a href="https://www.webmd.com/balance/stress-management/stress-management" data-metrics-link="" data-crosslink-type="article">\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li>Exercise regularly. Your body can fight stress better when it is fit.</li>\r\n	<li>Eat healthy, well-balanced meals.</li>\r\n	<li>Learn to manage your time more effectively.</li>\r\n	<li>Set limits appropriately and learn to say no to requests that would create excessive stress in your life.</li>\r\n	<li>Make time for hobbies, interests, and relaxation.</li>\r\n	<li>Get enough rest and sleep. Your body needs time to recover from stressful events.</li>\r\n	<li>Seek out social support. Spend enough time with those you enjoy.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Stress Management Tips', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'stress-management-tips__trashed', '', '', '2019-04-04 18:27:01', '2019-04-04 18:27:01', '', 0, 'http://www.drjchen.com/blog/?p=1253', 0, 'post', '', 0),
