(1331, 2, '2020-02-13 21:42:54', '2020-02-13 21:42:54', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tips for a Healthy\nValentine’s Day</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From intimate meals to\ndecadent desserts, couples across the globe will be celebrating romance this\nFebruary 14th. Love it or hate it, Valentine’s Day remains one of the biggest\nrestaurant nights of the year – one that often involves heavy dinners. But with\na few tips and some planning, you can get through the big night without adding\ninches to your waistline.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Step away from the\nbread basket</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you’d like a roll, grab one then move it\noutside of your reaching distance. The same goes for chips, should you be at a\nMexican restaurant. Grab a small handful and then stay away from them the rest\nof the night.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Meal modifications are key</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Feel free to make special requests. Ask the\nwaiter if they can put the sauce on the side – or to substitute veggies for the\nfrench fries. Find out if your meal can be made without butter, oil or\nsalt…anything that could help cut down on calories. And remember: in terms of\ncalories, grilled is usually better than fried and baked is better than\nbraised.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Start out healthy</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Consider ordering a light salad or soup to\nkick things off. This will help to fill you up before you dive into the big\nmeal. You also might want to split an entrée with your significant other.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Practice portion control</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Remember that restaurant sizes are often\nlarger than normal. Consider eating half of your meal and putting the rest in a\ndoggie bag.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Avoid all the bells and whistles</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Don’t add a bunch of extras to your meal. When\nit comes to a salad, avoid topping it off with buttery croutons, grated cheese,\nbacon and dollops of high-fat dressing. The same goes with a burger, baked\npotato and other entrees.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Think red</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Red bell peppers, radicchio, cherries,\nstrawberries, red beans, red onions and tomatoes, for example, are all packed\nwith vitamins, cancer-fighting antioxidants or cholesterol-busting fiber and\nprotein. In addition, a daily glass of red wine is believed to help reduce the\nrisk of blood clots and keep the cardiovascular system in shape. So forgo that\ncocktail, which can be loaded with sugar, and have a glass of red wine instead\n(and ask if they serve a light version).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Don''t always give the gift of chocolate</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you and your significant other are trying\nto lose or maintain weight, consider purchasing a fruit basket instead of a box\nof chocolate, or baking a low-calorie dessert. It’s also important to remember\nthat a number of sugar-free candies and chocolate brands are available and can\nbe found at your local grocery store or the candy section of an area pharmacy.\nA bouquet of flowers, healthy cookbook, personal training sessions or a day spa\ngift certificate could also prove worthy gift substitutes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Do not completely deprive yourself</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Valentine’s Day is a time for laughter, fun\nand food. Having a small slice of cake or a couple truffles will not lead to\nweight gain. Moderation is key. And if you do pop the lid off that box of\nchocolates this Valentine’s Day, don’t feel guilty. Research indicates\nchocolate is chock-full of healthy compounds and may actually help prevent\nheart disease, enhance immune systems and give us a feeling of well-being.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Consider dining in this year</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A great way to save calories, money and avoid\ncrowds. Find an easy reduced calorie meal that you can cook with or for your\nsignificant other at home. Rent some romantic movies and make a healthy\ndessert, like strawberry shortcake sprinkled with your favorite low-calorie\nsweetener, and enjoy!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Caloriecontrol.org</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Tips for Valentine''s Day', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'tips-for-valentines-day__trashed', '', '', '2020-03-16 18:45:08', '2020-03-16 18:45:08', '', 0, 'http://www.drjchen.com/blog/?p=1331', 0, 'post', '', 0);
